        </property>
        <property propertyId="67f102e2-9cb6-4d20-aa16-bf74d8a03326" amount="1.0" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7">
          <name xml:lang="en">wet mass</name>
          <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        </property>
        <productionVolumeComment xml:lang="en">Estimated value. The market for paint and plasters was estimated to be 182854 tons, of which 139445 tons for paint products and plasters, 6107 tons wood coatings, 37302 tons for others (including printing inks, wood preservatives and industrial coatings) (Hincapié et al. 2015). 
From the same study we extrapolate the tons of wall, wood and metal in C&amp;D waste, which is 1553tons (24% of total C&amp;D), 415 tons (6% of total C&amp;D), 354 tons (5% of total C&amp;D), respectively. 
To estimate the production volume we assumed that paint is 50% of the paint and plaster for construction category (hence 139445 * 0.5). Additionally of this 50%, 72% is assumed to be paint and 28% to be emulsion paint (FOEN 2013). Waste production is assumed to be 15% (taken from the estimated value for gypsum (WRAP, n.d).  This value is divided between wall, wood and metal accordingly to the percentage (found in Hincapié et al. 2015) of these materials in C&amp;D waste.
The treatment assumed in Hincapié et al. (2015) for paint products on wall is 77% recycling and 23% landfill; on concrete 90% recycling and 10% landfill; on wood 10% recycling and 90% incineration; on window glass 3% recycling and 97% landfill; on ferrous metal 98% recycling and 2% landfill; on non-ferrous metals 2% landfilled and 98%exported; on plastics 28% to recycling, 64% incineration and 8% landfill.
Source: Ingrid Hincapié, Alejandro Caballero-Guzmán, Bernd Nowack (2015) Nanomaterials in Landfills Module 3: Nanomaterials in Construction Waste. EMPA, Swiss Federal Laboratories for Materials Science and Technology. St. Gallen, Switzerland
FOEN (2013) Statistique des déchets spéciaux 2013. Retrieved from: &lt;http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/fr/index/themen/02/22/lexi.html&gt;, accessed 9th May 2016
WRAP (n.d.) International practice in plasterboard recycling: Canada. Retrieved from: http://www.wrap.org.uk/sites/files/wrap/Case%20study%20-%20Plasterboard%20recycling%20in%20Canada.pdf, accessed 3 May 2016</productionVolumeComment>
